        "title": "What is Cloud Computing?",
        "content": "### What is Cloud Computing?\n\nCloud computing is the **on-demand delivery of IT resources** over the internet with pay-as-you-use pricing. Instead of owning and maintaining physical data centers and servers, you can access technology services such as computing power, storage, and databases on an as-needed basis from cloud providers like AWS.\n\n#### Key Characteristics\n\n- **On-Demand Self-Service**: Provision resources automatically without human interaction\n- **Broad Network Access**: Services available over the network through standard mechanisms\n- **Resource Pooling**: Provider's resources are pooled to serve multiple consumers\n- **Rapid Elasticity**: Capabilities can scale up or down automatically\n- **Measured Service**: Resource usage is monitored, controlled, and reported\n\n#### Core Benefits\n\n**üí∞ Cost-Effectiveness**\n- Transform capital expenditures (CapEx) into operational expenditures (OpEx)\n- Pay only for resources you consume\n- *Example*: Instead of buying a $50,000 server that sits idle 70% of the time, pay for compute hours only when needed\n\n**‚ö° Scalability & Flexibility**\n- Scale resources up or down based on demand\n- Launch new services in minutes, not months\n- *Example*: An e-commerce site automatically scales during Black Friday sales\n\n**üåç Global Reach**\n- Deploy applications worldwide with just a few clicks\n- Reduce latency by placing resources closer to users\n\n**üîß Agility & Innovation**\n- Experiment with new technologies without large upfront investments\n- Focus on business logic rather than infrastructure management\n\nüí° **Real-World Example**: Netflix leverages cloud computing to serve 230+ million subscribers globally, automatically scaling their infrastructure during peak viewing times while only paying for resources actually used."
