        "title": "AWS Global Infrastructure",
        "content": "### AWS Global Infrastructure\n\nAWS operates the world's most comprehensive and broadly adopted cloud platform, spanning **84 Availability Zones** within **26 geographic Regions** around the world, with announced plans for more.\n\n#### Regions\n\n**Regions** are separate geographic areas where AWS clusters data centers. Each region is:\n- Completely isolated from other regions\n- Contains multiple Availability Zones\n- Allows you to place resources and data in multiple locations\n\n*Examples*: US East (N. Virginia), Europe (Ireland), Asia Pacific (Sydney)\n\nüéì **Choosing a Region considers**:\n- **Latency**: Proximity to your users\n- **Compliance**: Data sovereignty requirements\n- **Service Availability**: Not all services available in all regions\n- **Cost**: Pricing varies by region\n\n#### Availability Zones (AZs)\n\n**Availability Zones** are discrete data centers within a region, each with:\n- Redundant power, networking, and connectivity\n- Physical separation (typically miles apart)\n- High-bandwidth, low-latency networking between AZs\n\n*Example*: US East (N. Virginia) has 6 AZs: us-east-1a, us-east-1b, us-east-1c, etc.\n\n#### Edge Locations\n\n**Edge Locations** are data centers used by **Amazon CloudFront** (CDN service) to:\n- Cache content closer to users\n- Reduce latency for content delivery\n- Improve user experience globally\n\n‚ö†Ô∏è **Key Point**: There are **400+ edge locations** worldwide, far more than regions or AZs.\n\n#### Working Together\n\nüíé **Best Practice Example**: Deploy a web application across multiple AZs in a region for high availability, use CloudFront edge locations for fast content delivery, and replicate data to another region for disaster recovery."
