        "title": "Core AWS Service Categories",
        "content": "### Core AWS Service Categories\n\nAWS offers over **200 services** organized into logical categories. Understanding these core categories helps navigate the AWS ecosystem effectively.\n\n#### Compute Services\n\n**Purpose**: Provide processing power for applications\n\n- **Amazon EC2**: Virtual servers in the cloud\n- **AWS Lambda**: Serverless compute for code execution\n- **Amazon ECS/EKS**: Container orchestration services\n\n*Example*: Launch an EC2 instance to host a web server, or use Lambda to process uploaded images automatically.\n\n#### Storage Services\n\n**Purpose**: Store and retrieve data reliably and cost-effectively\n\n- **Amazon S3**: Object storage for websites, mobile apps, backup\n- **Amazon EBS**: Block storage for EC2 instances\n- **Amazon EFS**: Scalable file storage\n\n*Example*: Store website assets in S3, use EBS for database storage, share files across instances with EFS.\n\n#### Database Services\n\n**Purpose**: Managed database solutions for various use cases\n\n- **Amazon RDS**: Relational databases (MySQL, PostgreSQL, etc.)\n- **Amazon DynamoDB**: NoSQL database for high performance\n- **Amazon Redshift**: Data warehousing\n\n*Example*: Use RDS for an e-commerce application's product catalog, DynamoDB for session data.\n\n#### Networking Services\n\n**Purpose**: Connect resources securely and efficiently\n\n- **Amazon VPC**: Virtual private cloud networking\n- **Amazon CloudFront**: Content delivery network\n- **AWS Route 53**: DNS service\n\n#### Security Services\n\n**Purpose**: Protect data, applications, and infrastructure\n\n- **AWS IAM**: Identity and access management\n- **AWS Security Groups**: Virtual firewalls\n- **AWS KMS**: Key management service\n\nüîß **Practical Approach**: Start with compute (EC2), storage (S3), and database (RDS) services, then expand to networking and security as your architecture grows."
