        "title": "Shared Responsibility Model",
        "content": "### Shared Responsibility Model\n\nThe AWS **Shared Responsibility Model** defines the security responsibilities split between AWS and customers. This model varies depending on the service type and helps clarify \"who is responsible for what\" in cloud security.\n\n#### AWS Responsibilities: \"Security OF the Cloud\"\n\nAWS is responsible for protecting the infrastructure that runs all services:\n\n- **Physical Security**: Data centers, hardware, facilities\n- **Network Infrastructure**: Routers, switches, load balancers\n- **Hypervisor Security**: Virtualization layer protection\n- **Host Operating System**: Patching and maintenance\n- **Service Integration**: How services interact securely\n\n‚úÖ **What AWS Handles**: Physical access controls, environmental safeguards, network firewalls, hypervisor patches\n\n#### Customer Responsibilities: \"Security IN the Cloud\"\n\nCustomers are responsible for securing what they put in the cloud:\n\n- **Data Protection**: Encryption, classification, backup\n- **Identity & Access Management**: User permissions, MFA\n- **Operating System**: Guest OS updates and security patches\n- **Application Security**: Code vulnerabilities, SSL/TLS\n- **Network Security**: Security groups, NACLs, VPC configuration\n\n#### Service-Specific Variations\n\n**üîß Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) - EC2**\n- Customer manages: Guest OS, applications, data, network controls\n- *Example*: You patch the Windows Server running on your EC2 instance\n\n**üõ†Ô∏è Platform as a Service (PaaS) - RDS**\n- AWS manages: OS patching, database software updates\n- Customer manages: Database configuration, access controls, data\n\n**‚òÅÔ∏è Software as a Service (SaaS) - S3**\n- AWS manages: Infrastructure, platform, access logging\n- Customer manages: Data classification, bucket policies, access permissions\n\n‚ö†Ô∏è **Key Principle**: As you move up the service stack (IaaS ‚Üí PaaS ‚Üí SaaS), AWS takes on more responsibilities, but you never lose responsibility for your data and access management."
