        "title": "Amazon EC2 Fundamentals",
        "content": "### Amazon EC2 Fundamentals\n\n**Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2)** provides scalable virtual servers in the cloud, serving as the foundation for most AWS workloads. Think of EC2 as renting computers in Amazon's data centers that you can configure and manage remotely.\n\n#### Key Components\n\n**Instance Types** determine your virtual machine's specifications:\n- **t3.micro**: 1 vCPU, 1GB RAM - Perfect for testing and low-traffic websites\n- **m5.large**: 2 vCPUs, 8GB RAM - Balanced for general applications\n- **c5.xlarge**: 4 vCPUs, 8GB RAM - Optimized for CPU-intensive tasks\n\n**Amazon Machine Images (AMIs)** are pre-configured templates containing:\n- Operating system (Amazon Linux, Ubuntu, Windows)\n- Software packages and configurations\n- Security settings\n\nüéì **Example**: Launching a web server using Amazon Linux AMI with Apache pre-installed saves hours of manual setup.\n\n#### Basic Operations\n\n**Launching an Instance**:\n1. Choose AMI (e.g., Amazon Linux 2)\n2. Select instance type (t3.micro for testing)\n3. Configure security groups (allow HTTP/HTTPS traffic)\n4. Create or select key pair for SSH access\n\n**Managing Instances**:\n- **Start/Stop**: Control running state without losing data\n- **Terminate**: Permanently delete instance and associated storage\n- **Reboot**: Restart without data loss\n\nüí° **Cost Optimization**: Stop instances when not needed - you only pay for storage, not compute time.\n\n#### Practical Example\n\nLaunching a WordPress blog:\n```bash\n# Connect to your EC2 instance\nssh -i mykey.pem ec2-user@your-instance-ip\n\n# Install web server\nsudo yum update -y\nsudo yum install -y httpd\nsudo systemctl start httpd\n```\n\n‚ö†Ô∏è **Security Note**: Always use security groups to restrict access. Only open necessary ports (80 for web traffic, 22 for SSH from your IP).\n\nEC2 instances form the compute backbone that will connect to storage (S3) and networking (VPC) services we'll explore next."
