        "title": "Amazon S3 Storage",
        "content": "### Amazon S3 Storage\n\n**Amazon Simple Storage Service (S3)** provides unlimited object storage accessible from anywhere on the internet. Unlike traditional file systems, S3 stores files as objects in containers called buckets.\n\n#### Core Concepts\n\n**Buckets** are containers with globally unique names:\n- `my-company-website-assets`\n- `user-profile-photos-2024`\n- `application-backups-prod`\n\n**Objects** are files stored with metadata:\n- Maximum size: 5TB per object\n- Unlimited storage per bucket\n- Each object has a unique key (filename/path)\n\n#### Storage Classes\n\n| Class | Use Case | Cost | Retrieval |\n|-------|----------|------|-----------|\n| **Standard** | Frequently accessed data | Higher | Instant |\n| **IA (Infrequent Access)** | Monthly backups | Medium | Instant |\n| **Glacier** | Long-term archives | Lower | Minutes-hours |\n| **Deep Archive** | Compliance data | Lowest | 12+ hours |\n\nüéì **Example**: Store website images in Standard, monthly backups in IA, and compliance documents in Glacier.\n\n#### Common Use Cases\n\n**Web Application Storage**:\n```bash\n# Upload user profile photo\naws s3 cp profile.jpg s3://my-app-user-photos/user123/\n\n# Make publicly accessible\naws s3api put-object-acl --bucket my-app-user-photos --key user123/profile.jpg --acl public-read\n```\n\n**Static Website Hosting**:\n- Enable static website hosting on bucket\n- Upload HTML, CSS, JavaScript files\n- Access via: `http://bucket-name.s3-website-region.amazonaws.com`\n\n**Data Backup and Archival**:\n- Automatic lifecycle policies move old data to cheaper storage\n- Cross-region replication for disaster recovery\n\nüí° **Integration Example**: Your EC2 web server stores user uploads in S3, keeping compute and storage separate for better scalability.\n\n‚úÖ **Best Practices**:\n- Enable versioning for important data\n- Use bucket policies for access control\n- Set up lifecycle rules to optimize costs\n- Enable server-side encryption for sensitive data\n\nüîß **Real Scenario**: An e-commerce site stores product images in S3 Standard, uses CloudFront CDN for global delivery, and archives old transaction logs to Glacier after 1 year."
